s in the Americas, Eurasia, and Africa. Offering a unique global perspective, it explores common challenges and potential avenues for future progress in documenting domestication.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAnimal remains (Archaeology) 0aDomestic animalsxGenetics. 0aPlant remains (Archaeology) 0aPlants, CultivatedxGenetics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aBradley, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmshwiller, Eve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Bruce D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZeder, Melinda A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520932425.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles